==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Consumers surplus
<hw>Consumer's surplus</hw>. <fld>(Polit. econ.)</fld> <def>The excess
that a purchaser would be willing to pay for a commodity over that he
does pay, rather than go without the commodity; -- called also
<col><b>consumer's rent</b></col>.</def></p>

<p><q>The price which a person pays for a thing can never exceed, and
seldom comes up to, that which he would be willing to pay rather than go
without it. . . . The excess of the price which he would be willing to
pay rather than go without it, over that which he actually does pay, is
the economic measure of this surplus satisfaction. It has some analogies
to a rent; but is perhaps best called simply <qex>consumer's
surplus</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Alfred Marshall.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Consumingly</ent>⟦br⟧
